istic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Chao, Chue, Kao, Mee, Nou, Chai, Fong, Seng, Ying, Chou, Leng, See, Neng, Pao, Vang, Soua, Yer, Chong, Vue, Houa, Toua, Yeng, Youa, Blia, Mai, Bao, Da, Doa, Long, Thong, Dang, Hoa, Hue, Huong, Kha, Thao.","Southeast Asian (Hmong): from the name of the Lor or Lo clan of the Hmong people in Laos, China, and Vietnam; in Chinese characters it is written 羅 (see   Luo   1, compare 3 below). Compare   Lo   11.","Southeast Asian (Iu Mien): from the name of the Lor or Lo clan of the Iu Mien people from Laos. Compare   Law   6 and   Lo   12."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Marie De Lor was born about 1260. She had at least 1 son with Hervé De Cherisy. She died in Chérisy, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France."},"et":{"Abt 1260–":"umbes 1260–Surnud","1255–1301":"1255–1301","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","Abt 1260":"umbes 1260","1301":"1301","1255":"1255","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Chérisy, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Chérisy, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1260–":"noin 1260–Kuollut","1255–1301":"1255–1301","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","Abt 1260":"noin 1260","1301":"1301","1255":"1255","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Chérisy, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Chérisy, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Ranska"},"fr":{"Abt 1260–":"environ 1260–Décédée","1255–1301":"1255–1301","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1260–Female":"1260–Décédée","Abt 1260":"environ 1260","1301":"1301","1255":"1255","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Chérisy, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Chérisy, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France","lifeSummary":"Marie De Lor